{
  "text": "The study of variability within SC and FC each faces its unique limitations. Variation in acquisition, processing and connectome metrics as well as statistical methods may impact the extent of between-subjects variability observed. For instance, for SC, the diffusion method, tractography (Bonilha et al., 2015) , SC metric [CITATION_1] , or ROI size (Bonilha et al., 2015) , have been shown to affect variability and reproducibility of SCs. FC variability across subjects is affected by the choice of metric [CITATION_2] . For example, the amount of common variance may be slightly higher when using correlation compared to mutual information for the calculation of FC. On the other hand, the common component of FC that is invariant across subjects was comparable for dynamic and static FC [CITATION_3] . Nonetheless, the correlation between SC and FC may be limited by the dynamic fluctuation of FC on short time windows [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . SCs may better correlate with temporally stable rsFC [CITATION_7] . To this end, we considered only SC present connections in a secondary analysis, as these have been shown to have more stable resting-state FC .",
